
But as sales grew more than 20 percent a year through the 1990s organic food came to account for $1 of every $100 spent on food, and in 1997 the agency took notice, proposing national organic standards for all food. For years organic foods were bit players in the food industry. When the Agriculture Department proposed organic food regulations, more than 280,000 people filed comments protesting the inclusion of genetically modified foods as organic. Organic food has become an area of vigorous development in China's agriculture and food production. Talking about the future of the organic food industry, Liu Lianfu said organic food has already become a rising market with great potential. That should change with the release, as early as, in March 2000, of the first national standards for organic food. The government, on March 7, 2000, released new national standards for growing and processing organic food that will bar the use of genetic engineering or irradiation. New federal rules for organic food will assure consumers that the products are grown and processed to the same standards nationwide. It also offers a strict standard defining what constitutes an organic food, a step that should do a great deal to enhance consumer trust that a food labeled organic really is organic. They like to talk about (organic food), but they don't buy it. Like much of the rest of the world, the United States continues to lurch toward a national standard for organic food.

